data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_051ae35e55eb4ff2006998a8dbd0b8819791c7ba4a80f3a2b1","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":172,"text":"“**Foundry Agent Service**” most commonly refers to **Microsoft Foundry (Azure AI Foundry) Agent Service**: a managed runtime for building, deploying, and operating **AI agents** (not just chatbots) that can **use tools, follow workflows, and run with production controls**. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## What it is\nFoundry Agent Service is the part of Microsoft Foundry that “runs” your agent in production by connecting:\n- a **model** (LLM) deployment,\n- **tools** (search, data access, actions),\n- and platform capabilities like **safety, identity, networking, and observability**  \ninto a single managed service. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\nIn practice, it handles things like **conversation/thread state**, **tool orchestration** (calling the right tool at the right time), and **policy enforcement** so you can move from a demo to a governed production agent. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## What agents can do (typical workloads)\nMicrosoft positions this for business automation such as:\n- summarizing documents,\n- processing invoices,\n- managing support tickets,\n- publishing content,\n- and other repeatable workflows that need natural-language understanding plus actions. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## Tools (how agents get “capabilities”)\nAgent Service supports a catalog of tools you can attach so the agent can ground answers in data or take actions. Examples include: ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n- **Knowledge/data tools**: Azure AI Search, File Search, Microsoft Fabric, etc. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n- **Web grounding**: “Grounding with Bing Search” (and related options) to incorporate real-time public web data with citations. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/bing-grounding?view=foundry-classic))\n- **Action tools**: Azure Logic Apps, OpenAPI-based tools, MCP endpoints, function calling, Azure Functions, browser automation, and “Deep Research” style tooling (availability depends on API/portal experience). ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\nA key idea: during a “run,” the model can decide whether to invoke a tool (e.g., web search for “today’s news”), then use the tool output to produce the final answer. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## “Classic” vs “new” Foundry experience\nMicrosoft’s docs note there are **classic vs new portal/API experiences**, and some pages are specifically for the **classic agents API**. If you’re implementing this, it matters which experience your Foundry project is using because tools and APIs can differ. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## Quick clarifier\nWhen you say “Foundry,” do you mean **Microsoft Foundry (Azure AI Foundry)** or **Palantir Foundry**? The term “Foundry Agent Service” is strongly associated with Microsoft’s product in current documentation. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))"}

